Certainly! Angular is a powerful front-end framework that leverages several design patterns to promote maintainable, scalable, and testable code. Here are some of the most useful design patterns commonly used in Angular, along with practical examples:

---

### 1. **Component-Based Architecture**
Angular is built around components, which are the fundamental building blocks of the UI.

**Example:**
```ts
@Component({
  selector: 'app-user-card',
  template: `<div class="user-card">
    <h3>{{ user.name }}</h3>
    <p>{{ user.email }}</p>
  </div>`
})
export class UserCardComponent {
  @Input() user: User;
}
```

**Usage:**
```html
<app-user-card [user]="currentUser"></app-user-card>
```

> This promotes reusability and encapsulation.

---

### 2. **Dependency Injection (DI)**
Angular uses DI to provide services to components and other services, promoting loose coupling.

**Example:**
```ts
@Injectable({
  providedIn: 'root'
})
export class UserService {
  constructor(private http: HttpClient) {}

  getUsers(): Observable<User[]> {
    return this.http.get<User[]>('/api/users');
  }
}
```

